column168: AT APPROX 5:50 AM ON JUNE 18, 1986, A DRUM WAS PUNCTURED IN AN ATTEMPT TO A DD ADDITIONAL FREIGHT TO A TRAILER.  THERE WAS A SKID OF FREIGHT ALREADY ON THE TRAILER NEXT TO THE DRUMS ON THE RIGHT SIDE.  AN ATTEMPT WAS MADE TO A DD ADDITIONAL FREIGHT ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TRAILER.  WHILE LOADING THIS ADDITONAL FREIGHT, THE SKID ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRAILER WAS FORCED INT O ONE OF THE DRUMS CAUSING THE PUNCTURE.  LACK OF SUFFICIENT DUNNAGE BETWEE N THE DRUMS AND THE SKIDS WAS ALSO A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR.  THE PUNCTURE WAS DISCOVERED AT APPROX 6:00 AM.  THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK WAS REFERE NCED UNDER NA 2801.  THIS ADVISED TO REFERENCE GUIDE NO. 60.  THE INSTRUCTI ONS IN GUIDE 60 UNDER SPILLS OR LEAKS WAS FOLLOWED.  EMPLOYEES WERE MOVED T O FRESH AIR AND THE TRAILER WAS ISOLATED AT THE BACK OF TEH TERMINAL YARD. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT WAS NOTIFIED AT APPROX 6:40 AM AND AN EMERGENCY SERVIC E WAS CALLED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE CAN ON LY BE CORRECTED BY CONTINUED EDUCATION OF EMPLOYEES ON THE PROPER METHODS O F LOADING TRAILERS.  SUFFICIENT DUNNAGE MUST BE USED BETWEEN ANY TYPE OF DR UMS AND ROUGH FREIGHT THAT MAY BE ADDED.

column168: DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTING A LOAD OF REJECTED DRUMS FROM OUR CHEMICAL SECURE L ANDFILL IN PINEWOOD, SC TO REIDSVILLE, NC.  HE STOPPED IN COLUMBIA, SC TO P ICKUP ADDITIONAL DRUMS FROM ONE OF OUR CLIENTS.  WHILE ON CLIENT'S SITE, TH E DRIVER DISCOVERED A LEAK COMING FROM A DRUM IN THE NOSE OF HIS TRAILER. HE IMMEDIATELY COVERED THE SPILLED MATERIAL WITH AN ABSORBANT MEDIA, PLACED A 30 GALLON CONTAINER UNDER THE TRAILER TO CATCH ANY FURTHER LEAKAGE.  THE TRAILER WAS IMMEDIATELY OFF LOADED, THE LEAKING DRUM WAS LOCATED AND OVERP ACKED, THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND ABSORBANT WAS REMOVED AND PACKAGED FOR PROP ER DISPOSAL, AND THE PROPER AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED.  THE SPILL RESULTED IN A 2' X 3' AREA OF PAVEMENT BEING CONTAMINATED WITH LESS THAN ONE (1) GAL LON OF MATERIAL.  STATE OFFICIALS ARRIVED ON SCENE AND DEEMED THE SITE CLEA NED TO THEIR SATISFACTION AND THAT NO FOLLOWUP WOULD BE REQUIRED.

column168: THE ABOVE DESCRIBED INCIDENT EVOLVED AS THE DIRECT RESULT OF CONTAINER REAZ 287145 BEING OVER WEIGHT.  THE FREIGHT BILL DESCRIBING THE CONTENTS STATED PLASTIC CONTAINERS WERE BEING SHIPPED.  AS THE TRAILER WAS BEING STOWED INT O THE NUMBER THREE ENGINE COMPARTMENT ABOARD THE SS BAYAMON, TEJ BOTTOM RAI LS OF THE TRAILER FAILED TO SUPORT THE WEIGHT.  THIS CAUSED THE TRAILER TO BREAK OPEN AND DAMAGE CONTENTS.  WE PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD THE FREIGHT AT THE ACCIDENT LOCATION, HOWEVER, AS WE PROGRESSED INTO THE TRAILER WE FOUND 55 G ALLON DRUMS OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID.  SOME OF THESE DRUMS WERE LEAKING AND AS A RESULT TOXIC FUMES DEVELOPED.  TWO OF THE THE STEVEDORING PERSONNEL WERE AFFECTED BY THE FUMES AND BOTH HAD TO BE HOSPITALIZED.  THE JACKSONVILLE FI RE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED TO CONTAIN AND NEUTRALIZE THE SPILL.  THIS WAS ACC OMPLISHED AT APPROXIMATELY 0700 ON JUNE 26, 1986.  THE SPILL WAS LIMITED TO THE DECK OF OUR VESSEL AND NONE OF THE ACID WAS ALLOWED TO SEEP INTO ANY O PEN BODY OF WATER OF SOIL.  ATTACHED IS A COPY OF THE REPORT PROVIDED BY HA ZARDS, INC., THE CLEAN-UP COMPANY RESPONSIBLE FOR THE HANDLING OF THE AFFEC TED CARGO.  ALSO INCLUDED IS A COPY OF THE FREIGHT BILL ISSUED FOR THIS SHI PMENT.  ALL AGENCIES REQUIRED BY LAW WERE CONTACTED AS A RESULT OF THIS ACC IDENT.  THESE INCLUDED E.P.A. AND THE U.S. COAST GUARD.
